metadata.name: Stitched: Trauma #440
metadata.description:
"Every happy family is alike; every unhappy family is unhappy in its own way." -- Tolstoy

Stitched: trauma is based on the same code, and premise, as Stitched, with one twist: childhood trauma distorts experiences and events; some are wildly chaotic; others obsessively retrace a few curves. It is an experiment in combinatorial complexity: are two mints ever indistinguishable? 

The distortion has been carefully designed to allow a huge space of legibly distinct possibilities.

metadata.name: Euphonic #951
metadata.description:
Euphonic is an exploration of the emergent visual properties that arise from placing layers of simple lines atop one another.

In general this effect is called the Moir√© effect. This effect really feels best in the tactile - when you have a printed page and an acetate sheet. This piece attempts to recreate that tactile joy.

This is built in WebGL 2 and so doesn't work in Safari 14 and below. All latest browsers will work as expected.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.

metadata.name: The Face We Had #263
metadata.description:
The Face We Had is a series of generative, moving sculptures attempting to express the artists personal thoughts, experiences and inclinations related to meditative and altered states of consciousness. In a non-descriptive way, the piece aims to reflect the always changing nature of mind through patterns of movement and assemblages of form, color and organic shapes, endlessly revolving around a perceived point of origin.  

Although not intended as literal depictions, the elements interact in a way that could be interpreted as dance-like interactions between thought patterns, mental energy, feelings, fragments of memories and layers of personal identity. 



Interactive features:

space - pause/play
w - wireframe view
d - debug view (compute textures)
s - save screenshot

metadata.name: Paesaggio #227
metadata.description:
In this work I used the tools I learned in developing precedent works to generate a landscape with hills, flowers, streams, ruins, sky and clouds. The generated landscape gives the impression of a natural one but at the same time it has some "abstract" traits that reveal the geometrical properties of the noise generation process. This noise is used both for the morphological aspect and for colors assignment.

Developed with p5.js using WEBGL renderer.
Rendering is faster with chrome browser.

[s] to save a 1600x1600 png.


Features:
"Palette": 12 colormap
"Sky":  Day, Night, Gray - 15% Gray, 20% Night, 65% Day
"Ruins": True, False - 33% True
"Streams": True, False - 33% True
"Flower": Red-Blue, Fuchsia-Yellow, Rose-Violet
"Border": True, False - 25% True


Created by Andrea Belloni, fxhash: anbello, twitter: @Waterflowing0. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: Everything flows #141
metadata.description:
The Generative Token is obtained in two stages: in the first stage warped noise is generated using the method explained by Inigo Quilez (see Licence.txt for reference); in the second stage, using Sobel method for edge detection, the noise gradient orientation is used to generate flow lines.

The first stage generate an image colored using the values of warped noise.
The second stage generate another image using gradient orientations both for shapes (the flow lines) and for coloring.
The two images are blended together to obtain the final result.

In both stages the color-maps are generated using a sinusoidal function of the gradient orientation angle with a random phases. There are 52 possible combinations of random phases.
Some palette used in the second stage are re-mixed using simplex noise with 20% of probability.

The user can save a 1200x1200 png with 's'.

Sources of variations are:
- Four noise warping control parameters generating different grade of complexity and different shape (combined on a single number on the features)
- 52 generated color mapping for warped noise
- 52 generated color mapping for flow lines
- Blending of the two intermediate images

Features:
Grays: 25% of probability to have a grays palette, (True, False)
Color Palette: one of the 52 possible combinations of random phases
Color Mixing: 20% of probability to have a re-mixed palette
Noise Control: noise control parameter, (0 - 15)
Rare: when Grays = True and Noise Control < 4


Created by Andrea Belloni, fxhash: anbello, twitter: @Waterflowing0. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: Tangled #164
metadata.description:
"Tangled" is a generative art project that explores the emergent behaviour of simple shapes moving according to a random flow field. While the final result is always constrained to the shape of a circle, the variation within is endless.

Instructions:
Press "p" to pause the animation.
In live mode, press 1 through 5 to save a PNG version of the final result. The following resolutions are available:
1: 400 x 400 (ideal for Twitter PFP)
2: 1000 x 1000
3: 2000 x 2000
4: 4000 x 4000
5: 5000 x 5000
Please be patient, generating the PNG may take some time!

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: Breakers #244
metadata.description:
Companion project to Neural Collapse (#15780), for the collectors of my previous efforts.
A study on the repetition and stacking of a simple dynamic structure, this time inside a cylinder.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.

Interactivity : 
- You can click on each individual breaker to open or close them. The problem is it will toggle others.
- Press and hold the mouse button to slightly move the viewpoint. The previous interaction not being disabled while doing that, you get some switching all over the place as a bonus bug/feature.

- Press "a" to increase quality of the antialiasing (3 levels), at the cost of performances. If you don't like jaggies and your machine can take it.
- Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels. I recommend starting with "4".

GPU recommended. Best performances on Chrome in general.

metadata.name: Cosmic Type #230
metadata.description:
Cosmic Type is a kinetic type experiment that explores both graphic space as structural and semantic agency. Inspired by the early pioneering work of the concrete poets such as Dom Sylvester Hou√©dard, Ian Hamilton Finley and Steve McCaffe, the project is a play with letters, words and graphic form in the computational and generative space.

Each iteration gives you the possibility to discover a variety of visual form through exploring the system. Please explore your iteration with the key interactions below. It is hoped that you give the time to explore and observe. If you don't, you may end up with just a blank canvas. 

Thank you for collecting. 

Key Interactions

‚Äòa‚Äô activates forward motion on/off
‚Äòb‚Äô activates backward motion on/off
‚Äòr‚Äô rotates grid 45¬∞ [ rotates on key pressed]
‚Äòf‚Äô rotates the grid freely [ stops on key release ]
‚Äòp‚Äô switches grid scale on/off [ this can be CPU heavy on older machines ] 
‚Äòg‚Äô extra glyphs on/off
‚Äòq‚Äô return to the initial state 


Program written by Mark Webster
Font is copyright ¬©simonrenaud

metadata.name: Floatrest #206
metadata.description:
Floating forests over the endless sky, where birds, trees, plants, roots, rocks and waterfalls share an ecosystem full of life and emotion.

You can see some rain clouds in the sky and the sun shining under the raindrops.

The earth is moving, the blocks are falling, but the trees are strong in their roots.

Welcome to 'Floatrest'.

----

# Features

- 7 tree palettes
- 17 different background colors
- 10 different terrain colors
- clouds
- vines
- roots
- plants
- waterfall
- birds
- sun / moon
- night
- dark mode
- monochromatic
- 2 different aspect ratios (square & portrait)
- Press "p" on live mode to save in PNG

This artwork requires processing power and is intended for laptops and desktops primarily. It may take some time to render.

----

July 2022, gpitombo

metadata.name: Quantum Folly #268
metadata.description:
This piece explores humanity's vanity and obsession with controlling natural forces. In the end we are beholden to the whims of the universe and its rules. What we think is artificial is but nature's inclination.

As an atom gazes at the world it can see the arrogant hand of mankind imposing its will. We are nature's inane creation built from imperceptible, discrete particles.

Enjoy watching the structures form. Due to the nature of the system it may take some time to complete. Once it's fully rendered you can download a full resolution image of 3508 x 4961 px by ***double clicking/tapping***. At this size the piece is printable at A3 size at 300 dpi. If you're interested in acquiring a signed print please contact @KRANKARTA.

Features include: palette, orientation, architecture, particle rules, boundary seepage and colour displacement.

Created on Chrome desktop 103.0 on 2022-07-21 in javascript and GLSL. Results on other browsers/devices may vary.
